For example the informative consolidated version of the European Directive is somehow "applied by" an informative consolidated law in a European Union's member state.
http://schema.org/legislationAppliedBy.label: legislationAppliedBy

http://schema.org/legislationApplies.comment: Indicates that this legislation (or part of a legislation) somehow transfers another legislation in a different legislative context. This is an informative link, and it has no legal value. For legally-binding links of transposition, use the legislationTransposes property. For example an informative consolidated law of a European Union's member state "applies" the consolidated version of the European Directive implemented in it.
http://schema.org/legislationApplies.label: legislationApplies

http://schema.org/legislationChangedBy.comment: Another legislation that changes this legislation. This encompasses the notions of amendment, replacement, correction, repeal, or other types of change. This may be a direct change (textual or non-textual amendment) or a consequential or indirect change. The property is to be used to express the existence of a change relationship between two acts rather than the existence of a consolidated version of the text that shows the result of the change. For consolidation relationships, use the legislationConsolidatedBy property.
http://schema.org/legislationChangedBy.label: legislationChangedBy

http://schema.org/legislationChanges.comment: Another legislation that this legislation changes. This encompasses the notions of amendment, replacement, correction, repeal, or other types of change. This may be a direct change (textual or non-textual amendment) or a consequential or indirect change. The property is to be used to express the existence of a change relationship between two acts rather than the existence of a consolidated version of the text that shows the result of the change. For consolidation relationships, use the legislationConsolidates property.
http://schema.org/legislationChanges.label: legislationChanges

http://schema.org/legislationConsolidate.comment: Indicates a consolidated legislation (which is usually the product of an editorial process that revises the legislation) that take into account this legislation.
http://schema.org/legislationConsolidate.label: legislationConsolidatedBy

http://schema.org/legislationConsolidate.comment: Indicates another legislation taken into account in this consolidated legislation (which is usually the product of an editorial process that revises the legislation). This property should be used multiple times to refer to both the original version or the previous consolidated version, and to the legislations making the change.
http://schema.org/legislationConsolidate.label: legislationConsolidates

http://schema.org/legislationDate.comment: The date of adoption or signature of the legislation. This is the date at which the text is officially aknowledged to be a legislation, even though it might not even be published or in force.
http://schema.org/legislationDate.label: legislationDate

http://schema.org/legislationDateVersion.comment: The point-in-time at which the provided description of the legislation is valid (e.g. : when looking at the law on the 2016-04-07 (= dateVersion), I get the consolidation of 2015-04-12 of the "National Insurance Contributions Act 2015")
http://schema.org/legislationDateVersion.label: legislationDateVersion

http://schema.org/legislationIdentifier.comment: An identifier for the legislation. For example the CELEX at EU level, the NOR in France, or the ELI (European Legislation Identifier).
http://schema.org/legislationIdentifier.label: legislationIdentifier

http://schema.org/legislationLegalForce.comment: Whether the legislation is currently in force, not in force, or partially in force.
http://schema.org/legislationLegalForce.label: legislationLegalForce

http://schema.org/legislationLegalValue.comment: The legal value of this legislation file. The same legislation can be written in multiple files with different legal values. Typically a digitally signed PDF have a "stronger" legal value than the HTML file of the same act.
http://schema.org/legislationLegalValue.label: legislationLegalValue

http://schema.org/legislationPassedBy.comment: The person or organization that originally passed or made the law : typically parliament (for primary legislation) or government (for secondary legislation). This indicates the "legal author" of the law, as opposed to its physical author.
http://schema.org/legislationPassedBy.label: legislationPassedBy

http://schema.org/legislationResponsible.comment: An individual or organization that has some kind of responsibility for the legislation. Typically the ministry who is/was in charge of elaborating the legislation, or the adressee for potential questions about the legislation once it is published.
http://schema.org/legislationResponsible.label: legislationResponsible

http://schema.org/legislationTransposedB.comment: Indicates that the objectives set by this legislation (or part of legislation) are fulfilled by another legislation who passed appropriate implementation measures. Typically, European Directives are transposed by the legislations of European Union's member states or regions. This indicates a legally binding link between the 2 legislations.
http://schema.org/legislationTransposedB.label: legislationTransposedBy

http://schema.org/legislationTransposes.comment: Indicates that this legislation (or part of legislation) fulfills the objectives set by another legislation, by passing appropriate implementation measures. Typically, some legislations of European Union's member states or regions transpose European Directives. This indicates a legally binding link between the 2 legislations.
http://schema.org/legislationTransposes.label: legislationTransposes

http://schema.org/legislationType.comment: The type of the legislation. Examples of values are "law", "act", "directive", "decree", "regulation", "statutory instrument", "loi organique", "règlement grand-ducal", etc., depending on the country.
http://schema.org/legislationType.label: legislationType

http://schema.org/leiCode.comment: An organization identifier that uniquely identifies a legal entity as defined in ISO 17442.
http://schema.org/leiCode.label: leiCode

http://schema.org/lender.comment: A sub property of participant. The person that lends the object being borrowed.
http://schema.org/lender.label: lender

http://schema.org/lesser.comment: This ordering relation for qualitative values indicates that the subject is lesser than the object.
http://schema.org/lesser.label: lesser

http://schema.org/lesserOrEqual.comment: This ordering relation for qualitative values indicates that the subject is lesser than or equal to the object.
http://schema.org/lesserOrEqual.label: lesserOrEqual

http://schema.org/letterer.comment: The individual who adds lettering, including speech balloons and sound effects, to artwork.
http://schema.org/letterer.label: letterer

http://schema.org/license.comment: A license document that applies to this content, typically indicated by URL.
http://schema.org/license.label: license

http://schema.org/line.comment: A line is a point-to-point path consisting of two or more points. A line is expressed as a series of two or more point objects separated by space.
http://schema.org/line.label: line

http://schema.org/linkRelationship.comment: Indicates the relationship type of a Web link.
http://schema.org/linkRelationship.label: linkRelationship

http://schema.org/loanMortgageMandateAmo.comment: Amount of mortgage mandate that can be converted into a proper mortgage at a later stage.
http://schema.org/loanMortgageMandateAmo.label: loanMortgageMandateAmount

http://schema.org/loanPaymentAmount.comment: The amount of money to pay in a single payment.
http://schema.org/loanPaymentAmount.label: loanPaymentAmount

http://schema.org/loanPaymentFrequency.comment: Frequency of payments due, i.e. number of months between payments. This is defined as a frequency, i.e. the reciprocal of a period of time.
http://schema.org/loanPaymentFrequency.label: loanPaymentFrequency

http://schema.org/loanRepaymentForm.comment: A form of paying back money previously borrowed from a lender. Repayment usually takes the form of periodic payments that normally include part principal plus interest in each payment.
http://schema.org/loanRepaymentForm.label: loanRepaymentForm

http://schema.org/loanTerm.comment: The duration of the loan or credit agreement.
http://schema.org/loanTerm.label: loanTerm

http://schema.org/loanType.comment: The type of a loan or credit.
http://schema.org/loanType.label: loanType

http://schema.org/location.comment: The location of for example where the event is happening, an organization is located, or where an action takes place.
http://schema.org/location.label: location

http://schema.org/locationCreated.comment: The location where the CreativeWork was created, which may not be the same as the location depicted in the CreativeWork.
http://schema.org/locationCreated.label: locationCreated

http://schema.org/lodgingUnitDescription.comment: A full description of the lodging unit.
http://schema.org/lodgingUnitDescription.label: lodgingUnitDescription

http://schema.org/lodgingUnitType.comment: Textual description of the unit type (including suite vs. room, size of bed, etc.).
http://schema.org/lodgingUnitType.label: lodgingUnitType

http://schema.org/longitude.comment: The longitude of a location. For example -122.08585 (WGS 84).
http://schema.org/longitude.label: longitude

http://schema.org/loser.comment: A sub property of participant. The loser of the action.
http://schema.org/loser.label: loser

http://schema.org/lowPrice.comment: The lowest price of all offers available.
http://schema.org/lowPrice.label: lowPrice

http://schema.org/lyricist.comment: The person who wrote the words.
http://schema.org/lyricist.label: lyricist

http://schema.org/mainContentOfPage.comment: Indicates if this web page element is the main subject of the page.
http://schema.org/mainContentOfPage.label: mainContentOfPage

http://schema.org/mainEntity.comment: Indicates the primary entity described in some page or other CreativeWork.
http://schema.org/mainEntity.label: mainEntity

http://schema.org/mainEntityOfPage.comment: Indicates a page (or other CreativeWork) for which this thing is the main entity being described. See background notes for details.
http://schema.org/mainEntityOfPage.label: mainEntityOfPage

http://schema.org/makesOffer.comment: A pointer to products or services offered by the organization or person.
http://schema.org/makesOffer.label: makesOffer

http://schema.org/map.comment: A URL to a map of the place.
http://schema.org/map.label: map

http://schema.org/mapType.comment: Indicates the kind of Map, from the MapCategoryType Enumeration.
http://schema.org/mapType.label: mapType

http://schema.org/maps.comment: A URL to a map of the place.
http://schema.org/maps.label: maps

http://schema.org/masthead.comment: For a NewsMediaOrganization, a link to the masthead page or a page listing top editorial management.
http://schema.org/masthead.label: masthead

http://schema.org/material.comment: A material that something is made from, e.g. leather, wool, cotton, paper.
http://schema.org/material.label: material

http://schema.org/maxPrice.comment: The highest price if the price is a range.
http://schema.org/maxPrice.label: maxPrice

http://schema.org/maxValue.comment: The upper value of some characteristic or property.
http://schema.org/maxValue.label: maxValue

http://schema.org/maximumAttendeeCapacit.comment: The total number of individuals that may attend an event or venue.
http://schema.org/maximumAttendeeCapacit.label: maximumAttendeeCapacity

http://schema.org/maximumIntake.comment: Recommended intake of this supplement for a given population as defined by a specific recommending authority.
http://schema.org/maximumIntake.label: maximumIntake

http://schema.org/mealService.comment: Description of the meals that will be provided or available for purchase.
http://schema.org/mealService.label: mealService

http://schema.org/measurementTechnique.comment:
A technique or technology used in a Dataset (or DataDownload, DataCatalog), corresponding to the method used for measuring the corresponding variable(s) (described using variableMeasured). This is oriented towards scientific and scholarly dataset publication but may have broader applicability; it is not intended as a full representation of measurement, but rather as a high level summary for dataset discovery.

For example, if variableMeasured is: molecule concentration, measurementTechnique could be: "mass spectrometry" or "nmr spectroscopy" or "colorimetry" or "immunofluorescence".

If the variableMeasured is "depression rating", the measurementTechnique could be "Zung Scale" or "HAM-D" or "Beck Depression Inventory".

If there are several variableMeasured properties recorded for some given data object, use a PropertyValue for each variableMeasured and attach the corresponding measurementTechnique.
http://schema.org/measurementTechnique.label: measurementTechnique

http://schema.org/mechanismOfAction.comment: The specific biochemical interaction through which this drug or supplement produces its pharmacological effect.
http://schema.org/mechanismOfAction.label: mechanismOfAction

http://schema.org/medicalSpecialty.comment: A medical specialty of the provider.
http://schema.org/medicalSpecialty.label: medicalSpecialty

http://schema.org/medicineSystem.comment: The system of medicine that includes this MedicalEntity, for example 'evidence-based', 'homeopathic', 'chiropractic', etc.
http://schema.org/medicineSystem.label: medicineSystem

http://schema.org/meetsEmissionStandard.comment: Indicates that the vehicle meets the respective emission standard.
http://schema.org/meetsEmissionStandard.label: meetsEmissionStandard

http://schema.org/member.comment: A member of an Organization or a ProgramMembership. Organizations can be members of organizations; ProgramMembership is typically for individuals.
http://schema.org/member.label: member

http://schema.org/memberOf.comment: An Organization (or ProgramMembership) to which this Person or Organization belongs.
http://schema.org/memberOf.label: memberOf

http://schema.org/membershipNumber.comment: A unique identifier for the membership.
http://schema.org/membershipNumber.label: membershipNumber

http://schema.org/mentions.comment: Indicates that the CreativeWork contains a reference to, but is not necessarily about a concept.
http://schema.org/mentions.label: mentions

http://schema.org/menu.comment: Either the actual menu as a structured representation, as text, or a URL of the menu.
http://schema.org/menu.label: menu

http://schema.org/menuAddOn.comment: Additional menu item(s) such as a side dish of salad or side order of fries that can be added to this menu item. Additionally it can be a menu section containing allowed add-on menu items for this menu item.
http://schema.org/menuAddOn.label: menuAddOn

http://schema.org/messageAttachment.comment: A CreativeWork attached to the message.
http://schema.org/messageAttachment.label: messageAttachment

http://schema.org/mileageFromOdometer.comment:
The total distance travelled by the particular vehicle since its initial production, as read from its odometer.

Typical unit code(s): KMT for kilometers, SMI for statute miles
http://schema.org/mileageFromOdometer.label: mileageFromOdometer

http://schema.org/minPrice.comment: The lowest price if the price is a range.
http://schema.org/minPrice.label: minPrice

http://schema.org/minValue.comment: The lower value of some characteristic or property.
http://schema.org/minValue.label: minValue

http://schema.org/minimumPaymentDue.comment: The minimum payment required at this time.
http://schema.org/minimumPaymentDue.label: minimumPaymentDue

http://schema.org/missionCoveragePriorit.comment: For a NewsMediaOrganization, a statement on coverage priorities, including any public agenda or stance on issues.
http://schema.org/missionCoveragePriorit.label: missionCoveragePrioritiesPolicy

http://schema.org/model.comment: The model of the product. Use with the URL of a ProductModel or a textual representation of the model identifier. The URL of the ProductModel can be from an external source. It is recommended to additionally provide strong product identifiers via the gtin8/gtin13/gtin14 and mpn properties.
http://schema.org/model.label: model

http://schema.org/modelDate.comment: The release date of a vehicle model (often used to differentiate versions of the same make and model).
http://schema.org/modelDate.label: modelDate

http://schema.org/modifiedTime.comment: The date and time the reservation was modified.
http://schema.org/modifiedTime.label: modifiedTime

http://schema.org/monthlyMinimumRepaymen.comment: The minimum payment is the lowest amount of money that one is required to pay on a credit card statement each month.
http://schema.org/monthlyMinimumRepaymen.label: monthlyMinimumRepaymentAmount

http://schema.org/mpn.comment: The Manufacturer Part Number (MPN) of the product, or the product to which the offer refers.
http://schema.org/mpn.label: mpn

http://schema.org/multipleValues.comment: Whether multiple values are allowed for the property.  Default is false.
http://schema.org/multipleValues.label: multipleValues

http://schema.org/musicArrangement.comment: An arrangement derived from the composition.
http://schema.org/musicArrangement.label: musicArrangement

http://schema.org/musicCompositionForm.comment: The type of composition (e.g. overture, sonata, symphony, etc.).
http://schema.org/musicCompositionForm.label: musicCompositionForm

http://schema.org/musicGroupMember.comment: A member of a music group—for example, John, Paul, George, or Ringo.
http://schema.org/musicGroupMember.label: musicGroupMember

http://schema.org/musicReleaseFormat.comment: Format of this release (the type of recording media used, ie. compact disc, digital media, LP, etc.).
http://schema.org/musicReleaseFormat.label: musicReleaseFormat

http://schema.org/musicalKey.comment: The key, mode, or scale this composition uses.
http://schema.org/musicalKey.label: musicalKey

http://schema.org/naics.comment: The North American Industry Classification System (NAICS) code for a particular organization or business person.
http://schema.org/naics.label: naics

http://schema.org/namedPosition.comment: A position played, performed or filled by a person or organization, as part of an organization. For example, an athlete in a SportsTeam might play in the position named 'Quarterback'.
http://schema.org/namedPosition.label: namedPosition

http://schema.org/naturalProgression.comment: The expected progression of the condition if it is not treated and allowed to progress naturally.
http://schema.org/naturalProgression.label: naturalProgression

http://schema.org/nerve.comment: The underlying innervation associated with the muscle.
http://schema.org/nerve.label: nerve

http://schema.org/nerveMotor.comment: The neurological pathway extension that involves muscle control.
http://schema.org/nerveMotor.label: nerveMotor

http://schema.org/netWorth.comment: The total financial value of the person as calculated by subtracting assets from liabilities.
http://schema.org/netWorth.label: netWorth

http://schema.org/nextItem.comment: A link to the ListItem that follows the current one.
http://schema.org/nextItem.label: nextItem

http://schema.org/nonEqual.comment: This ordering relation for qualitative values indicates that the subject is not equal to the object.
http://schema.org/nonEqual.label: nonEqual

http://schema.org/nonProprietaryName.comment: The generic name of this drug or supplement.
http://schema.org/nonProprietaryName.label: nonProprietaryName

http://schema.org/normalRange.comment: Range of acceptable values for a typical patient, when applicable.
http://schema.org/normalRange.label: normalRange

http://schema.org/numAdults.comment: The number of adults staying in the unit.
http://schema.org/numAdults.label: numAdults

http://schema.org/numChildren.comment: The number of children staying in the unit.
http://schema.org/numChildren.label: numChildren

http://schema.org/numTracks.comment: The number of tracks in this album or playlist.
http://schema.org/numTracks.label: numTracks

http://schema.org/numberOfAirbags.comment: The number or type of airbags in the vehicle.
http://schema.org/numberOfAirbags.label: numberOfAirbags

http://schema.org/numberOfAxles.comment:
The number of axles.

Typical unit code(s): C62
http://schema.org/numberOfAxles.label: numberOfAxles

http://schema.org/numberOfBeds.comment: The quantity of the given bed type available in the HotelRoom, Suite, House, or Apartment.
http://schema.org/numberOfBeds.label: numberOfBeds

http://schema.org/numberOfDoors.comment:
The number of doors.

Typical unit code(s): C62
http://schema.org/numberOfDoors.label: numberOfDoors

http://schema.org/numberOfEmployees.comment: The number of employees in an organization e.g. business.
http://schema.org/numberOfEmployees.label: numberOfEmployees

http://schema.org/numberOfEpisodes.comment: The number of episodes in this season or series.
http://schema.org/numberOfEpisodes.label: numberOfEpisodes

http://schema.org/numberOfForwardGears.comment:
The total number of forward gears available for the transmission system of the vehicle.

Typical unit code(s): C62
http://schema.org/numberOfForwardGears.label: numberOfForwardGears

http://schema.org/numberOfItems.comment: The number of items in an ItemList. Note that some descriptions might not fully describe all items in a list (e.g., multi-page pagination); in such cases, the numberOfItems would be for the entire list.
http://schema.org/numberOfItems.label: numberOfItems

http://schema.org/numberOfLoanPayments.comment: The number of payments contractually required at origination to repay the loan. For monthly paying loans this is the number of months from the contractual first payment date to the maturity date.
http://schema.org/numberOfLoanPayments.label: numberOfLoanPayments

http://schema.org/numberOfPages.comment: The number of pages in the book.
http://schema.org/numberOfPages.label: numberOfPages

http://schema.org/numberOfPlayers.comment: Indicate how many people can play this game (minimum, maximum, or range).
http://schema.org/numberOfPlayers.label: numberOfPlayers

http://schema.org/numberOfPreviousOwners.comment:
The number of owners of the vehicle, including the current one.

Typical unit code(s): C62
http://schema.org/numberOfPreviousOwners.label: numberOfPreviousOwners

http://schema.org/numberOfRooms.comment:
The number of rooms (excluding bathrooms and closets) of the acccommodation or lodging business.
Typical unit code(s): ROM for room or C62 for no unit. The type of room can be put in the unitText property of the QuantitativeValue.
http://schema.org/numberOfRooms.label: numberOfRooms

http://schema.org/numberOfSeasons.comment: The number of seasons in this series.
http://schema.org/numberOfSeasons.label: numberOfSeasons

http://schema.org/numberedPosition.comment: A number associated with a role in an organization, for example, the number on an athlete's jersey.
http://schema.org/numberedPosition.label: numberedPosition

http://schema.org/nutrition.comment: Nutrition information about the recipe or menu item.
http://schema.org/nutrition.label: nutrition

http://schema.org/object.comment: The object upon which the action is carried out, whose state is kept intact or changed. Also known as the semantic roles patient, affected or undergoer (which change their state) or theme (which doesn't). e.g. John read a book.
http://schema.org/object.label: object

http://schema.org/occupancy.comment:
The allowed total occupancy for the accommodation in persons (including infants etc). For individual accommodations, this is not necessarily the legal maximum but defines the permitted usage as per the contractual agreement (e.g. a double room used by a single person).
Typical unit code(s): C62 for person
http://schema.org/occupancy.label: occupancy

http://schema.org/occupationalCategory.comment: Category or categories describing the job. Use BLS O*NET-SOC taxonomy: http://www.onetcenter.org/taxonomy.html. Ideally includes textual label and formal code, with the property repeated for each applicable value.
http://schema.org/occupationalCategory.label: occupationalCategory

http://schema.org/offerCount.comment: The number of offers for the product.
http://schema.org/offerCount.label: offerCount

http://schema.org/offeredBy.comment: A pointer to the organization or person making the offer.
http://schema.org/offeredBy.label: offeredBy

http://schema.org/offers.comment: An offer to provide this item—for example, an offer to sell a product, rent the DVD of a movie, perform a service, or give away tickets to an event.
http://schema.org/offers.label: offers

http://schema.org/offersPrescriptionByMa.comment: Whether prescriptions can be delivered by mail.
http://schema.org/offersPrescriptionByMa.label: offersPrescriptionByMail

http://schema.org/openingHours.comment:
The general opening hours for a business. Opening hours can be specified as a weekly time range, starting with days, then times per day. Multiple days can be listed with commas ',' separating each day. Day or time ranges are specified using a hyphen '-'.

  • Days are specified using the following two-letter combinations: Mo, Tu, We, Th, Fr, Sa, Su.
  • Times are specified using 24:00 time. For example, 3pm is specified as 15:00.
  • Here is an example: <time itemprop="openingHours" datetime="Tu,Th 16:00-20:00">Tuesdays and Thursdays 4-8pm</time>.
  • If a business is open 7 days a week, then it can be specified as <time itemprop="openingHours" datetime="Mo-Su">Monday through Sunday, all day</time>.
http://schema.org/openingHours.label: openingHours

http://schema.org/openingHoursSpecificat.comment: The opening hours of a certain place.
http://schema.org/openingHoursSpecificat.label: openingHoursSpecification

http://schema.org/opens.comment: The opening hour of the place or service on the given day(s) of the week.
http://schema.org/opens.label: opens

http://schema.org/opponent.comment: A sub property of participant. The opponent on this action.
http://schema.org/opponent.label: opponent

http://schema.org/option.comment: A sub property of object. The options subject to this action.
http://schema.org/option.label: option

http://schema.org/orderDelivery.comment: The delivery of the parcel related to this order or order item.
http://schema.org/orderDelivery.label: orderDelivery

http://schema.org/orderItemNumber.comment: The identifier of the order item.
http://schema.org/orderItemNumber.label: orderItemNumber

http://schema.org/orderItemStatus.comment: The current status of the order item.
http://schema.org/orderItemStatus.label: orderItemStatus

http://schema.org/orderQuantity.comment: The number of the item ordered. If the property is not set, assume the quantity is one.
http://schema.org/orderQuantity.label: orderQuantity

http://schema.org/orderStatus.comment: The current status of the order.
http://schema.org/orderStatus.label: orderStatus

http://schema.org/origin.comment: The place or point where a muscle arises.
http://schema.org/origin.label: origin

http://schema.org/originatesFrom.comment: The vasculature the lymphatic structure originates, or afferents, from.
http://schema.org/originatesFrom.label: originatesFrom

http://schema.org/outcome.comment: Expected or actual outcomes of the study.
http://schema.org/outcome.label: outcome

http://schema.org/overdosage.comment: Any information related to overdose on a drug, including signs or symptoms, treatments, contact information for emergency response.
http://schema.org/overdosage.label: overdosage

http://schema.org/overview.comment: Descriptive information establishing the overarching theory/philosophy of the plan. May include the rationale for the name, the population where the plan first came to prominence, etc.
http://schema.org/overview.label: overview

http://schema.org/ownedFrom.comment: The date and time of obtaining the product.
http://schema.org/ownedFrom.label: ownedFrom

http://schema.org/ownedThrough.comment: The date and time of giving up ownership on the product.
http://schema.org/ownedThrough.label: ownedThrough

http://schema.org/owns.comment: Products owned by the organization or person.
http://schema.org/owns.label: owns

http://schema.org/pageEnd.comment: The page on which the work ends; for example "138" or "xvi".
http://schema.org/pageEnd.label: pageEnd

http://schema.org/pageStart.comment: The page on which the work starts; for example "135" or "xiii".
http://schema.org/pageStart.label: pageStart

http://schema.org/pagination.comment: Any description of pages that is not separated into pageStart and pageEnd; for example, "1-6, 9, 55" or "10-12, 46-49".
http://schema.org/pagination.label: pagination

http://schema.org/parentItem.comment: The parent of a question, answer or item in general.
http://schema.org/parentItem.label: parentItem

http://schema.org/parentOrganization.comment: The larger organization that this organization is a subOrganization of, if any.
http://schema.org/parentOrganization.label: parentOrganization

http://schema.org/parentService.comment: A broadcast service to which the broadcast service may belong to such as regional variations of a national channel.
http://schema.org/parentService.label: parentService

http://schema.org/partOfEpisode.comment: The episode to which this clip belongs.
http://schema.org/partOfEpisode.label: partOfEpisode

http://schema.org/partOfInvoice.comment: The order is being paid as part of the referenced Invoice.
http://schema.org/partOfInvoice.label: partOfInvoice

http://schema.org/partOfOrder.comment: The overall order the items in this delivery were included in.
http://schema.org/partOfOrder.label: partOfOrder

http://schema.org/partOfSeason.comment: The season to which this episode belongs.
http://schema.org/partOfSeason.label: partOfSeason

http://schema.org/partOfSeries.comment: The series to which this episode or season belongs.
http://schema.org/partOfSeries.label: partOfSeries

http://schema.org/partOfSystem.comment: The anatomical or organ system that this structure is part of.
http://schema.org/partOfSystem.label: partOfSystem

http://schema.org/partOfTVSeries.comment: The TV series to which this episode or season belongs.
http://schema.org/partOfTVSeries.label: partOfTVSeries

http://schema.org/participant.comment: Other co-agents that participated in the action indirectly. e.g. John wrote a book with Steve.
http://schema.org/participant.label: participant

http://schema.org/partySize.comment: Number of people the reservation should accommodate.
http://schema.org/partySize.label: partySize

http://schema.org/passengerPriorityStatu.comment: The priority status assigned to a passenger for security or boarding (e.g. FastTrack or Priority).
http://schema.org/passengerPriorityStatu.label: passengerPriorityStatus

http://schema.org/passengerSequenceNumbe.comment: The passenger's sequence number as assigned by the airline.
http://schema.org/passengerSequenceNumbe.label: passengerSequenceNumber

http://schema.org/pathophysiology.comment: Changes in the normal mechanical, physical, and biochemical functions that are associated with this activity or condition.
http://schema.org/pathophysiology.label: pathophysiology

http://schema.org/payload.comment:
The permitted weight of passengers and cargo, EXCLUDING the weight of the empty vehicle.

Typical unit code(s): KGM for kilogram, LBR for pound

  • Note 1: Many databases specify the permitted TOTAL weight instead, which is the sum of weight and payload
  • Note 2: You can indicate additional information in the name of the QuantitativeValue node.
  • Note 3: You may also link to a QualitativeValue node that provides additional information using valueReference.
  • Note 4: Note that you can use minValue and maxValue to indicate ranges.
http://schema.org/payload.label: payload

http://schema.org/paymentDue.comment: The date that payment is due.
http://schema.org/paymentDue.label: paymentDue

http://schema.org/paymentDueDate.comment: The date that payment is due.
http://schema.org/paymentDueDate.label: paymentDueDate

http://schema.org/paymentMethod.comment: The name of the credit card or other method of payment for the order.
http://schema.org/paymentMethod.label: paymentMethod

http://schema.org/paymentMethodId.comment: An identifier for the method of payment used (e.g. the last 4 digits of the credit card).
http://schema.org/paymentMethodId.label: paymentMethodId

http://schema.org/paymentStatus.comment: The status of payment; whether the invoice has been paid or not.
http://schema.org/paymentStatus.label: paymentStatus

http://schema.org/paymentUrl.comment: The URL for sending a payment.
http://schema.org/paymentUrl.label: paymentUrl

http://schema.org/penciler.comment: The individual who draws the primary narrative artwork.
http://schema.org/penciler.label: penciler

http://schema.org/performTime.comment: The length of time it takes to perform instructions or a direction (not including time to prepare the supplies), in ISO 8601 duration format.
http://schema.org/performTime.label: performTime

http://schema.org/performer.comment: A performer at the event—for example, a presenter, musician, musical group or actor.
http://schema.org/performer.label: performer

http://schema.org/performerIn.comment: Event that this person is a performer or participant in.
http://schema.org/performerIn.label: performerIn

http://schema.org/performers.comment: The main performer or performers of the event—for example, a presenter, musician, or actor.
http://schema.org/performers.label: performers

http://schema.org/permissionType.comment: The type of permission granted the person, organization, or audience.
http://schema.org/permissionType.label: permissionType

http://schema.org/permissions.comment: Permission(s) required to run the app (for example, a mobile app may require full internet access or may run only on wifi).
http://schema.org/permissions.label: permissions

http://schema.org/permitAudience.comment: The target audience for this permit.
http://schema.org/permitAudience.label: permitAudience

http://schema.org/permittedUsage.comment: Indications regarding the permitted usage of the accommodation.
http://schema.org/permittedUsage.label: permittedUsage

http://schema.org/petsAllowed.comment: Indicates whether pets are allowed to enter the accommodation or lodging business. More detailed information can be put in a text value.
http://schema.org/petsAllowed.label: petsAllowed

http://schema.org/phase.comment: The phase of the clinical trial.
http://schema.org/phase.label: phase

http://schema.org/physiologicalBenefits.comment: Specific physiologic benefits associated to the plan.
http://schema.org/physiologicalBenefits.label: physiologicalBenefits

http://schema.org/pickupLocation.comment: Where a taxi will pick up a passenger or a rental car can be picked up.
http://schema.org/pickupLocation.label: pickupLocation

http://schema.org/pickupTime.comment: When a taxi will pickup a passenger or a rental car can be picked up.
http://schema.org/pickupTime.label: pickupTime

http://schema.org/playMode.comment: Indicates whether this game is multi-player, co-op or single-player.  The game can be marked as multi-player, co-op and single-player at the same time.
http://schema.org/playMode.label: playMode

http://schema.org/playerType.comment: Player type required—for example, Flash or Silverlight.
http://schema.org/playerType.label: playerType

http://schema.org/playersOnline.comment: Number of players on the server.
http://schema.org/playersOnline.label: playersOnline

http://schema.org/polygon.comment: A polygon is the area enclosed by a point-to-point path for which the starting and ending points are the same. A polygon is expressed as a series of four or more space delimited points where the first and final points are identical.
http://schema.org/polygon.label: polygon

http://schema.org/population.comment: Any characteristics of the population used in the study, e.g. 'males under 65'.
http://schema.org/population.label: population

http://schema.org/position.comment: The position of an item in a series or sequence of items.
http://schema.org/position.label: position

http://schema.org/possibleComplication.comment: A possible unexpected and unfavorable evolution of a medical condition. Complications may include worsening of the signs or symptoms of the disease, extension of the condition to other organ systems, etc.
http://schema.org/possibleComplication.label: possibleComplication

http://schema.org/possibleTreatment.comment: A possible treatment to address this condition, sign or symptom.
http://schema.org/possibleTreatment.label: possibleTreatment

http://schema.org/postOfficeBoxNumber.comment: The post office box number for PO box addresses.
http://schema.org/postOfficeBoxNumber.label: postOfficeBoxNumber

http://schema.org/postOp.comment: A description of the postoperative procedures, care, and/or followups for this device.
http://schema.org/postOp.label: postOp

http://schema.org/potentialAction.comment: Indicates a potential Action, which describes an idealized action in which this thing would play an 'object' role.
http://schema.org/potentialAction.label: potentialAction

http://schema.org/preOp.comment: A description of the workup, testing, and other preparations required before implanting this device.
http://schema.org/preOp.label: preOp

http://schema.org/predecessorOf.comment: A pointer from a previous, often discontinued variant of the product to its newer variant.
http://schema.org/predecessorOf.label: predecessorOf

http://schema.org/pregnancyWarning.comment: Any precaution, guidance, contraindication, etc. related to this drug's use during pregnancy.
http://schema.org/pregnancyWarning.label: pregnancyWarning

http://schema.org/prepTime.comment: The length of time it takes to prepare the items to be used in instructions or a direction, in ISO 8601 duration format.
http://schema.org/prepTime.label: prepTime

http://schema.org/preparation.comment: Typical preparation that a patient must undergo before having the procedure performed.
http://schema.org/preparation.label: preparation

http://schema.org/prescribingInfo.comment: Link to prescribing information for the drug.
http://schema.org/prescribingInfo.label: prescribingInfo

http://schema.org/prescriptionStatus.comment: Indicates the status of drug prescription eg. local catalogs classifications or whether the drug is available by prescription or over-the-counter, etc.
http://schema.org/prescriptionStatus.label: prescriptionStatus

http://schema.org/previousItem.comment: A link to the ListItem that preceeds the current one.
http://schema.org/previousItem.label: previousItem

http://schema.org/previousStartDate.comment: Used in conjunction with eventStatus for rescheduled or cancelled events. This property contains the previously scheduled start date. For rescheduled events, the startDate property should be used for the newly scheduled start date. In the (rare) case of an event that has been postponed and rescheduled multiple times, this field may be repeated.
http://schema.org/previousStartDate.label: previousStartDate

http://schema.org/price.comment:
The offer price of a product, or of a price component when attached to PriceSpecification and its subtypes.

Usage guidelines:

  • Use the priceCurrency property (with ISO 4217 codes e.g. "USD") instead of including ambiguous symbols such as '$' in the value.
  • Use '.' (Unicode 'FULL STOP' (U+002E)) rather than ',' to indicate a decimal point. Avoid using these symbols as a readability separator.
  • Note that both RDFa and Microdata syntax allow the use of a "content=" attribute for publishing simple machine-readable values alongside more human-friendly formatting.
  • Use values from 0123456789 (Unicode 'DIGIT ZERO' (U+0030) to 'DIGIT NINE' (U+0039)) rather than superficially similiar Unicode symbols.
http://schema.org/price.label: price

http://schema.org/priceComponent.comment: This property links to all UnitPriceSpecification nodes that apply in parallel for the CompoundPriceSpecification node.
http://schema.org/priceComponent.label: priceComponent

http://schema.org/priceCurrency.comment: The currency (in 3-letter ISO 4217 format) of the price or a price component, when attached to PriceSpecification and its subtypes.
http://schema.org/priceCurrency.label: priceCurrency

http://schema.org/priceRange.comment: The price range of the business, for example $$$.
http://schema.org/priceRange.label: priceRange

http://schema.org/priceSpecification.comment: One or more detailed price specifications, indicating the unit price and delivery or payment charges.
http://schema.org/priceSpecification.label: priceSpecification

http://schema.org/priceType.comment: A short text or acronym indicating multiple price specifications for the same offer, e.g. SRP for the suggested retail price or INVOICE for the invoice price, mostly used in the car industry.
http://schema.org/priceType.label: priceType

http://schema.org/priceValidUntil.comment: The date after which the price is no longer available.
http://schema.org/priceValidUntil.label: priceValidUntil

http://schema.org/primaryImageOfPage.comment: Indicates the main image on the page.
http://schema.org/primaryImageOfPage.label: primaryImageOfPage

http://schema.org/primaryPrevention.comment: A preventative therapy used to prevent an initial occurrence of the medical condition, such as vaccination.
http://schema.org/primaryPrevention.label: primaryPrevention

http://schema.org/printColumn.comment: The number of the column in which the NewsArticle appears in the print edition.
http://schema.org/printColumn.label: printColumn

http://schema.org/printEdition.comment: The edition of the print product in which the NewsArticle appears.
http://schema.org/printEdition.label: printEdition

http://schema.org/printPage.comment: If this NewsArticle appears in print, this field indicates the name of the page on which the article is found. Please note that this field is intended for the exact page name (e.g. A5, B18).
http://schema.org/printPage.label: printPage

http://schema.org/printSection.comment: If this NewsArticle appears in print, this field indicates the print section in which the article appeared.
http://schema.org/printSection.label: printSection

http://schema.org/procedure.comment: A description of the procedure involved in setting up, using, and/or installing the device.
http://schema.org/procedure.label: procedure

http://schema.org/procedureType.comment: The type of procedure, for example Surgical, Noninvasive, or Percutaneous.
http://schema.org/procedureType.label: procedureType

http://schema.org/processingTime.comment: Estimated processing time for the service using this channel.
http://schema.org/processingTime.label: processingTime

http://schema.org/processorRequirements.comment: Processor architecture required to run the application (e.g. IA64).
http://schema.org/processorRequirements.label: processorRequirements

http://schema.org/producer.comment: The person or organization who produced the work (e.g. music album, movie, tv/radio series etc.).
http://schema.org/producer.label: producer

http://schema.org/produces.comment: The tangible thing generated by the service, e.g. a passport, permit, etc.
http://schema.org/produces.label: produces

http://schema.org/productID.comment: The product identifier, such as ISBN. For example: meta itemprop="productID" content="isbn:123-456-789".
http://schema.org/productID.label: productID

http://schema.org/productSupported.comment: The product or service this support contact point is related to (such as product support for a particular product line). This can be a specific product or product line (e.g. "iPhone") or a general category of products or services (e.g. "smartphones").

http://schema.org/speakable.comment:
Indicates sections of a Web page that are particularly 'speakable' in the sense of being highlighted as being especially appropriate for text-to-speech conversion. Other sections of a page may also be usefully spoken in particular circumstances; the 'speakable' property serves to indicate the parts most likely to be generally useful for speech.

The speakable property can be repeated an arbitrary number of times, with three kinds of possible 'content-locator' values:

1.) id-value URL references - uses id-value of an element in the page being annotated. The simplest use of speakable has (potentially relative) URL values, referencing identified sections of the document concerned.

2.) CSS Selectors - addresses content in the annotated page, eg. via class attribute. Use the cssSelector property.

3.) XPaths - addresses content via XPaths (assuming an XML view of the content). Use the xpath property.

For more sophisticated markup of speakable sections beyond simple ID references, either CSS selectors or XPath expressions to pick out document section(s) as speakable. For this we define a supporting type, SpeakableSpecification which is defined to be a possible value of the speakable property.
http://schema.org/speakable.label: speakable

http://schema.org/workload.comment: Quantitative measure of the physiologic output of the exercise; also referred to as energy expenditure.
http://schema.org/workload.label: workload

http://schema.org/worksFor.comment: Organizations that the person works for.
http://schema.org/worksFor.label: worksFor

http://schema.org/worstRating.comment: The lowest value allowed in this rating system. If worstRating is omitted, 1 is assumed.
http://schema.org/worstRating.label: worstRating

http://schema.org/yearlyRevenue.comment: The size of the business in annual revenue.
http://schema.org/yearlyRevenue.label: yearlyRevenue

http://schema.org/yield.comment: The quantity that results by performing instructions. For example, a paper airplane, 10 personalized candles.
http://schema.org/yield.label: yield

http://schema.org/AMRadioChannel.comment: A radio channel that uses AM.
http://schema.org/AMRadioChannel.label: AMRadioChannel

http://schema.org/APIReference.comment: Reference documentation for application programming interfaces (APIs).
http://schema.org/APIReference.label: APIReference

http://schema.org/AcceptAction.comment:
The act of committing to/adopting an object.

Related actions:

  • RejectAction: The antonym of AcceptAction.
http://schema.org/AcceptAction.label: AcceptAction

http://schema.org/Accommodation.comment:
An accommodation is a place that can accommodate human beings, e.g. a hotel room, a camping pitch, or a meeting room. Many accommodations are for overnight stays, but this is not a mandatory requirement. For more specific types of accommodations not defined in schema.org, one can use additionalType with external vocabularies.

See also the dedicated document on the use of schema.org for marking up hotels and other forms of accommodations.
http://schema.org/Accommodation.label: Accommodation

http://schema.org/AccountingService.comment:
Accountancy business.

As a LocalBusiness it can be described as a provider of one or more Service(s).
http://schema.org/AccountingService.label: AccountingService

http://schema.org/AchieveAction.comment: The act of accomplishing something via previous efforts. It is an instantaneous action rather than an ongoing process.
http://schema.org/AchieveAction.label: AchieveAction

http://schema.org/Action.comment:
An action performed by a direct agent and indirect participants upon a direct object. Optionally happens at a location with the help of an inanimate instrument. The execution of the action may produce a result. Specific action sub-type documentation specifies the exact expectation of each argument/role.

See also blog post and Actions overview document.
http://schema.org/Action.label: Action

http://schema.org/ActivateAction.comment: The act of starting or activating a device or application (e.g. starting a timer or turning on a flashlight).
http://schema.org/ActivateAction.label: ActivateAction

http://schema.org/AddAction.comment: The act of editing by adding an object to a collection.
http://schema.org/AddAction.label: AddAction

http://schema.org/AdministrativeArea.comment: A geographical region, typically under the jurisdiction of a particular government.
http://schema.org/AdministrativeArea.label: AdministrativeArea

http://schema.org/AdvertiserContentArtic.comment: An Article that an external entity has paid to place or to produce to its specifications. Includes advertorials, sponsored content, native advertising and other paid content.
http://schema.org/AdvertiserContentArtic.label: AdvertiserContentArticle

http://schema.org/AggregateOffer.comment: When a single product is associated with multiple offers (for example, the same pair of shoes is offered by different merchants), then AggregateOffer can be used.
http://schema.org/AggregateOffer.label: AggregateOffer

http://schema.org/AggregateRating.comment: The average rating based on multiple ratings or reviews.
http://schema.org/AggregateRating.label: AggregateRating

http://schema.org/AgreeAction.comment: The act of expressing a consistency of opinion with the object. An agent agrees to/about an object (a proposition, topic or theme) with participants.
http://schema.org/AgreeAction.label: AgreeAction

http://schema.org/Airline.comment: An organization that provides flights for passengers.
http://schema.org/Airline.label: Airline

http://schema.org/AlignmentObject.comment: An intangible item that describes an alignment between a learning resource and a node in an educational framework.
http://schema.org/AlignmentObject.label: AlignmentObject

http://schema.org/AllocateAction.comment: The act of organizing tasks/objects/events by associating resources to it.
http://schema.org/AllocateAction.label: AllocateAction

http://schema.org/AnalysisNewsArticle.comment: An AnalysisNewsArticle is a NewsArticle that, while based on factual reporting, incorporates the expertise of the author/producer, offering interpretations and conclusions.
http://schema.org/AnalysisNewsArticle.label: AnalysisNewsArticle

http://schema.org/AnatomicalStructure.comment: Any part of the human body, typically a component of an anatomical system. Organs, tissues, and cells are all anatomical structures.
http://schema.org/AnatomicalStructure.label: AnatomicalStructure

http://schema.org/AnatomicalSystem.comment: An anatomical system is a group of anatomical structures that work together to perform a certain task. Anatomical systems, such as organ systems, are one organizing principle of anatomy, and can includes circulatory, digestive, endocrine, integumentary, immune, lymphatic, muscular, nervous, reproductive, respiratory, skeletal, urinary, vestibular, and other systems.
http://schema.org/AnatomicalSystem.label: AnatomicalSystem

http://schema.org/Answer.comment: An answer offered to a question; perhaps correct, perhaps opinionated or wrong.
http://schema.org/Answer.label: Answer

http://schema.org/Apartment.comment: An apartment (in American English) or flat (in British English) is a self-contained housing unit (a type of residential real estate) that occupies only part of a building (Source: Wikipedia, the free encyclopedia, see http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Apartment).
http://schema.org/Apartment.label: Apartment

http://schema.org/AppendAction.comment: The act of inserting at the end if an ordered collection.
http://schema.org/AppendAction.label: AppendAction

http://schema.org/ApplyAction.comment:
The act of registering to an organization/service without the guarantee to receive it.

Related actions:

  • RegisterAction: Unlike RegisterAction, ApplyAction has no guarantees that the application will be accepted.
http://schema.org/ApplyAction.label: ApplyAction

http://schema.org/ApprovedIndication.comment: An indication for a medical therapy that has been formally specified or approved by a regulatory body that regulates use of the therapy; for example, the US FDA approves indications for most drugs in the US.
http://schema.org/ApprovedIndication.label: ApprovedIndication

http://schema.org/ArriveAction.comment: The act of arriving at a place. An agent arrives at a destination from a fromLocation, optionally with participants.
http://schema.org/ArriveAction.label: ArriveAction

http://schema.org/Artery.comment: A type of blood vessel that specifically carries blood away from the heart.
http://schema.org/Artery.label: Artery

http://schema.org/Article.comment:
An article, such as a news article or piece of investigative report. Newspapers and magazines have articles of many different types and this is intended to cover them all.

See also blog post.
http://schema.org/Article.label: Article

http://schema.org/AskAction.comment:
The act of posing a question / favor to someone.

Related actions:

  • ReplyAction: Appears generally as a response to AskAction.
http://schema.org/AskAction.label: AskAction

http://schema.org/AssessAction.comment: The act of forming one's opinion, reaction or sentiment.
http://schema.org/AssessAction.label: AssessAction

http://schema.org/AssignAction.comment: The act of allocating an action/event/task to some destination (someone or something).
http://schema.org/AssignAction.label: AssignAction

http://schema.org/Atlas.comment: A collection or bound volume of maps, charts, plates or tables, physical or in media form illustrating any subject.
http://schema.org/Atlas.label: Atlas

http://schema.org/Attorney.comment:
Professional service: Attorney.

This type is deprecated - LegalService is more inclusive and less ambiguous.
http://schema.org/Attorney.label: Attorney

http://schema.org/Audience.comment: Intended audience for an item, i.e. the group for whom the item was created.
http://schema.org/Audience.label: Audience

http://schema.org/AuthorizeAction.comment: The act of granting permission to an object.
http://schema.org/AuthorizeAction.label: AuthorizeAction

http://schema.org/BackgroundNewsArticle.comment: A NewsArticle providing historical context, definition and detail on a specific topic (aka "explainer" or "backgrounder"). For example, an in-depth article or frequently-asked-questions (FAQ) document on topics such as Climate Change or the European Union. Other kinds of background material from a non-news setting are often described using Book or Article, in particular ScholarlyArticle. See also NewsArticle for related vocabulary from a learning/education perspective.
http://schema.org/BackgroundNewsArticle.label: BackgroundNewsArticle

http://schema.org/BankAccount.comment: A product or service offered by a bank whereby one may deposit, withdraw or transfer money and in some cases be paid interest.
http://schema.org/BankAccount.label: BankAccount

http://schema.org/Barcode.comment: An image of a visual machine-readable code such as a barcode or QR code.
http://schema.org/Barcode.label: Barcode

http://schema.org/BedAndBreakfast.comment:
Bed and breakfast.

See also the dedicated document on the use of schema.org for marking up hotels and other forms of accommodations.
http://schema.org/BedAndBreakfast.label: BedAndBreakfast

http://schema.org/BedDetails.comment: An entity holding detailed information about the available bed types, e.g. the quantity of twin beds for a hotel room. For the single case of just one bed of a certain type, you can use bed directly with a text. See also BedType (under development).
http://schema.org/BedDetails.label: BedDetails

http://schema.org/BedType.comment: A type of bed. This is used for indicating the bed or beds available in an accommodation.
http://schema.org/BedType.label: BedType

http://schema.org/BefriendAction.comment:
The act of forming a personal connection with someone (object) mutually/bidirectionally/symmetrically.

Related actions:

  • FollowAction: Unlike FollowAction, BefriendAction implies that the connection is reciprocal.
http://schema.org/BefriendAction.label: BefriendAction

http://schema.org/BloodTest.comment: A medical test performed on a sample of a patient's blood.
http://schema.org/BloodTest.label: BloodTest

http://schema.org/BoardingPolicyType.comment: A type of boarding policy used by an airline.
http://schema.org/BoardingPolicyType.label: BoardingPolicyType

http://schema.org/BodyOfWater.comment: A body of water, such as a sea, ocean, or lake.
http://schema.org/BodyOfWater.label: BodyOfWater

http://schema.org/Bone.comment: Rigid connective tissue that comprises up the skeletal structure of the human body.
http://schema.org/Bone.label: Bone

http://schema.org/BookFormatType.comment: The publication format of the book.
http://schema.org/BookFormatType.label: BookFormatType

http://schema.org/BookSeries.comment: A series of books. Included books can be indicated with the hasPart property.
http://schema.org/BookSeries.label: BookSeries

http://schema.org/BorrowAction.comment:
The act of obtaining an object under an agreement to return it at a later date. Reciprocal of LendAction.

Related actions:

  • LendAction: Reciprocal of BorrowAction.
http://schema.org/BorrowAction.label: BorrowAction

http://schema.org/BrainStructure.comment: Any anatomical structure which pertains to the soft nervous tissue functioning as the coordinating center of sensation and intellectual and nervous activity.
http://schema.org/BrainStructure.label: BrainStructure

http://schema.org/Brand.comment: A brand is a name used by an organization or business person for labeling a product, product group, or similar.
http://schema.org/Brand.label: Brand

http://schema.org/BreadcrumbList.comment:
A BreadcrumbList is an ItemList consisting of a chain of linked Web pages, typically described using at least their URL and their name, and typically ending with the current page.

The position property is used to reconstruct the order of the items in a BreadcrumbList The convention is that a breadcrumb list has an itemListOrder of ItemListOrderAscending (lower values listed first), and that the first items in this list correspond to the "top" or beginning of the breadcrumb trail, e.g. with a site or section homepage. The specific values of 'position' are not assigned meaning for a BreadcrumbList, but they should be integers, e.g. beginning with '1' for the first item in the list.
http://schema.org/BreadcrumbList.label: BreadcrumbList

http://schema.org/BroadcastChannel.comment: A unique instance of a BroadcastService on a CableOrSatelliteService lineup.
http://schema.org/BroadcastChannel.label: BroadcastChannel

http://schema.org/BroadcastEvent.comment: An over the air or online broadcast event.
http://schema.org/BroadcastEvent.label: BroadcastEvent

http://schema.org/BroadcastFrequencySpec.comment: The frequency in MHz and the modulation used for a particular BroadcastService.
http://schema.org/BroadcastFrequencySpec.label: BroadcastFrequencySpecification

http://schema.org/BroadcastService.comment: A delivery service through which content is provided via broadcast over the air or online.
http://schema.org/BroadcastService.label: BroadcastService

http://schema.org/BrokerageAccount.comment: An account that allows an investor to deposit funds and place investment orders with a licensed broker or brokerage firm.
http://schema.org/BrokerageAccount.label: BrokerageAccount

http://schema.org/BusOrCoach.comment: A bus (also omnibus or autobus) is a road vehicle designed to carry passengers. Coaches are luxury busses, usually in service for long distance travel.
http://schema.org/BusOrCoach.label: BusOrCoach

http://schema.org/BusReservation.comment:
A reservation for bus travel.

Note: This type is for information about actual reservations, e.g. in confirmation emails or HTML pages with individual confirmations of reservations. For offers of tickets, use Offer.
http://schema.org/BusReservation.label: BusReservation

http://schema.org/BusTrip.comment: A trip on a commercial bus line.
http://schema.org/BusTrip.label: BusTrip

http://schema.org/BusinessAudience.comment: A set of characteristics belonging to businesses, e.g. who compose an item's target audience.
http://schema.org/BusinessAudience.label: BusinessAudience

http://schema.org/BusinessEntityType.comment:
A business entity type is a conceptual entity representing the legal form, the size, the main line of business, the position in the value chain, or any combination thereof, of an organization or business person.

Commonly used values:

  • http://purl.org/goodrelations/v1#Business
  • http://purl.org/goodrelations/v1#Enduser
  • http://purl.org/goodrelations/v1#PublicInstitution
  • http://purl.org/goodrelations/v1#Reseller
http://schema.org/BusinessEntityType.label: BusinessEntityType

http://schema.org/BusinessFunction.comment:
The business function specifies the type of activity or access (i.e., the bundle of rights) offered by the organization or business person through the offer. Typical are sell, rental or lease, maintenance or repair, manufacture / produce, recycle / dispose, engineering / construction, or installation. Proprietary specifications of access rights are also instances of this class.

Commonly used values:

  • http://purl.org/goodrelations/v1#ConstructionInstallation
  • http://purl.org/goodrelations/v1#Dispose
  • http://purl.org/goodrelations/v1#LeaseOut
  • http://purl.org/goodrelations/v1#Maintain
  • http://purl.org/goodrelations/v1#ProvideService
  • http://purl.org/goodrelations/v1#Repair
  • http://purl.org/goodrelations/v1#Sell
  • http://purl.org/goodrelations/v1#Buy
http://schema.org/BusinessFunction.label: BusinessFunction

http://schema.org/BuyAction.comment: The act of giving money to a seller in exchange for goods or services rendered. An agent buys an object, product, or service from a seller for a price. Reciprocal of SellAction.
http://schema.org/BuyAction.label: BuyAction

http://schema.org/CableOrSatelliteServic.comment: A service which provides access to media programming like TV or radio. Access may be via cable or satellite.
http://schema.org/CableOrSatelliteServic.label: CableOrSatelliteService

http://schema.org/Campground.comment:
A camping site, campsite, or campground is a place used for overnight stay in the outdoors. In British English a campsite is an area, usually divided into a number of pitches, where people can camp overnight using tents or camper vans or caravans; this British English use of the word is synonymous with the American English expression campground. In American English the term campsite generally means an area where an individual, family, group, or military unit can pitch a tent or parks a camper; a campground may contain many campsites (Source: Wikipedia, the free encyclopedia, see http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Campsite).

See also the dedicated document on the use of schema.org for marking up hotels and other forms of accommodations.
http://schema.org/Campground.label: Campground

http://schema.org/CampingPitch.comment:
A camping pitch is an individual place for overnight stay in the outdoors, typically being part of a larger camping site.

See also the dedicated document on the use of schema.org for marking up hotels and other forms of accommodations.
http://schema.org/CampingPitch.label: CampingPitch

http://schema.org/Canal.comment: A canal, like the Panama Canal.
http://schema.org/Canal.label: Canal

http://schema.org/CancelAction.comment:
The act of asserting that a future event/action is no longer going to happen.

Related actions:

  • ConfirmAction: The antonym of CancelAction.
http://schema.org/CancelAction.label: CancelAction

http://schema.org/Car.comment: A car is a wheeled, self-powered motor vehicle used for transportation.
http://schema.org/Car.label: Car

http://schema.org/CarUsageType.comment: A value indicating a special usage of a car, e.g. commercial rental, driving school, or as a taxi.
http://schema.org/CarUsageType.label: CarUsageType

http://schema.org/CategoryCodeSet.comment: A set of Category Code values.
http://schema.org/CategoryCodeSet.label: CategoryCodeSet

http://schema.org/Chapter.comment: One of the sections into which a book is divided. A chapter usually has a section number or a name.
http://schema.org/Chapter.label: Chapter

http://schema.org/CheckAction.comment: An agent inspects, determines, investigates, inquires, or examines an object's accuracy, quality, condition, or state.
http://schema.org/CheckAction.label: CheckAction

http://schema.org/CheckInAction.comment:
The act of an agent communicating (service provider, social media, etc) their arrival by registering/confirming for a previously reserved service (e.g. flight check in) or at a place (e.g. hotel), possibly resulting in a result (boarding pass, etc).

Related actions:

  • CheckOutAction: The antonym of CheckInAction.
  • ArriveAction: Unlike ArriveAction, CheckInAction implies that the agent is informing/confirming the start of a previously reserved service.
  • ConfirmAction: Unlike ConfirmAction, CheckInAction implies that the agent is informing/confirming the start of a previously reserved service rather than its validity/existence.
http://schema.org/CheckInAction.label: CheckInAction

http://schema.org/CheckOutAction.comment:
The act of an agent communicating (service provider, social media, etc) their departure of a previously reserved service (e.g. flight check in) or place (e.g. hotel).

Related actions:

  • CheckInAction: The antonym of CheckOutAction.
  • DepartAction: Unlike DepartAction, CheckOutAction implies that the agent is informing/confirming the end of a previously reserved service.
  • CancelAction: Unlike CancelAction, CheckOutAction implies that the agent is informing/confirming the end of a previously reserved service.
http://schema.org/CheckOutAction.label: CheckOutAction

http://schema.org/ChooseAction.comment: The act of expressing a preference from a set of options or a large or unbounded set of choices/options.
http://schema.org/ChooseAction.label: ChooseAction

http://schema.org/CivicStructure.comment: A public structure, such as a town hall or concert hall.
http://schema.org/CivicStructure.label: CivicStructure

http://schema.org/ClaimReview.comment: A fact-checking review of claims made (or reported) in some creative work (referenced via itemReviewed).
http://schema.org/ClaimReview.label: ClaimReview

http://schema.org/Class.comment: A class, also often called a 'Type'; equivalent to rdfs:Class.
http://schema.org/Class.label: Class

http://schema.org/Clip.comment: A short TV or radio program or a segment/part of a program.
http://schema.org/Clip.label: Clip

http://schema.org/Code.comment: Computer programming source code. Example: Full (compile ready) solutions, code snippet samples, scripts, templates.
http://schema.org/Code.label: Code

http://schema.org/Collection.comment: A created collection of Creative Works or other artefacts.
http://schema.org/Collection.label: Collection

http://schema.org/CollegeOrUniversity.comment: A college, university, or other third-level educational institution.
http://schema.org/CollegeOrUniversity.label: CollegeOrUniversity

http://schema.org/ComicCoverArt.comment: The artwork on the cover of a comic.
http://schema.org/ComicCoverArt.label: ComicCoverArt

http://schema.org/ComicIssue.comment:
Individual comic issues are serially published as
    part of a larger series. For the sake of consistency, even one-shot issues
    belong to a series comprised of a single issue. All comic issues can be
    uniquely identified by: the combination of the name and volume number of the
    series to which the issue belongs; the issue number; and the variant
    description of the issue (if any).
http://schema.org/ComicIssue.label: ComicIssue

http://schema.org/ComicSeries.comment:
A sequential publication of comic stories under a
    unifying title, for example "The Amazing Spider-Man" or "Groo the
    Wanderer".
http://schema.org/ComicSeries.label: ComicSeries

http://schema.org/ComicStory.comment:
The term "story" is any indivisible, re-printable
    unit of a comic, including the interior stories, covers, and backmatter. Most
    comics have at least two stories: a cover (ComicCoverArt) and an interior story.
http://schema.org/ComicStory.label: ComicStory

http://schema.org/Comment.comment: A comment on an item - for example, a comment on a blog post. The comment's content is expressed via the text property, and its topic via about, properties shared with all CreativeWorks.
http://schema.org/Comment.label: Comment

http://schema.org/CommentAction.comment: The act of generating a comment about a subject.
http://schema.org/CommentAction.label: CommentAction

http://schema.org/CommunicateAction.comment: The act of conveying information to another person via a communication medium (instrument) such as speech, email, or telephone conversation.
http://schema.org/CommunicateAction.label: CommunicateAction

http://schema.org/CompleteDataFeed.comment:
A CompleteDataFeed is a DataFeed whose standard representation includes content for every item currently in the feed.

This is the equivalent of Atom's element as defined in Feed Paging and Archiving RFC 5005, For example (and as defined for Atom), when using data from a feed that represents a collection of items that varies over time (e.g. "Top Twenty Records") there is no need to have newer entries mixed in alongside older, obsolete entries. By marking this feed as a CompleteDataFeed, old entries can be safely discarded when the feed is refreshed, since we can assume the feed has provided descriptions for all current items.
http://schema.org/CompleteDataFeed.label: CompleteDataFeed

http://schema.org/CompoundPriceSpecifica.comment: A compound price specification is one that bundles multiple prices that all apply in combination for different dimensions of consumption. Use the name property of the attached unit price specification for indicating the dimension of a price component (e.g. "electricity" or "final cleaning").
http://schema.org/CompoundPriceSpecifica.label: CompoundPriceSpecification

http://schema.org/ComputerLanguage.comment: This type covers computer programming languages such as Scheme and Lisp, as well as other language-like computer representations. Natural languages are best represented with the Language type.
http://schema.org/ComputerLanguage.label: ComputerLanguage

http://schema.org/ConfirmAction.comment:
The act of notifying someone that a future event/action is going to happen as expected.

Related actions:

  • CancelAction: The antonym of ConfirmAction.
http://schema.org/ConfirmAction.label: ConfirmAction

http://schema.org/Consortium.comment: A Consortium is a membership Organization whose members are typically Organizations.
http://schema.org/Consortium.label: Consortium

http://schema.org/ContactPoint.comment: A contact point—for example, a Customer Complaints department.
http://schema.org/ContactPoint.label: ContactPoint

http://schema.org/ContactPointOption.comment: Enumerated options related to a ContactPoint.
http://schema.org/ContactPointOption.label: ContactPointOption

http://schema.org/Continent.comment: One of the continents (for example, Europe or Africa).
http://schema.org/Continent.label: Continent

http://schema.org/ControlAction.comment: An agent controls a device or application.
http://schema.org/ControlAction.label: ControlAction

http://schema.org/Conversation.comment: One or more messages between organizations or people on a particular topic. Individual messages can be linked to the conversation with isPartOf or hasPart properties.
http://schema.org/Conversation.label: Conversation

http://schema.org/Course.comment: A description of an educational course which may be offered as distinct instances at which take place at different times or take place at different locations, or be offered through different media or modes of study. An educational course is a sequence of one or more educational events and/or creative works which aims to build knowledge, competence or ability of learners.
http://schema.org/Course.label: Course

http://schema.org/CourseInstance.comment: An instance of a Course which is distinct from other instances because it is offered at a different time or location or through different media or modes of study or to a specific section of students.
http://schema.org/CourseInstance.label: CourseInstance

http://schema.org/CoverArt.comment: The artwork on the outer surface of a CreativeWork.
http://schema.org/CoverArt.label: CoverArt

http://schema.org/CreateAction.comment: The act of deliberately creating/producing/generating/building a result out of the agent.
http://schema.org/CreateAction.label: CreateAction

http://schema.org/CreativeWork.comment: The most generic kind of creative work, including books, movies, photographs, software programs, etc.
http://schema.org/CreativeWork.label: CreativeWork

http://schema.org/CreativeWorkSeason.comment: A media season e.g. tv, radio, video game etc.
http://schema.org/CreativeWorkSeason.label: CreativeWorkSeason

http://schema.org/CreativeWorkSeries.comment:
A CreativeWorkSeries in schema.org is a group of related items, typically but not necessarily of the same kind. CreativeWorkSeries are usually organized into some order, often chronological. Unlike ItemList which is a general purpose data structure for lists of things, the emphasis with CreativeWorkSeries is on published materials (written e.g. books and periodicals, or media such as tv, radio and games).

Specific subtypes are available for describing TVSeries, RadioSeries, MovieSeries, BookSeries, Periodical and VideoGameSeries. In each case, the hasPart / isPartOf properties can be used to relate the CreativeWorkSeries to its parts. The general CreativeWorkSeries type serves largely just to organize these more specific and practical subtypes.

It is common for properties applicable to an item from the series to be usefully applied to the containing group. Schema.org attempts to anticipate some of these cases, but publishers should be free to apply properties of the series parts to the series as a whole wherever they seem appropriate.
http://schema.org/CreativeWorkSeries.label: CreativeWorkSeries

http://schema.org/CreditCard.comment:
A card payment method of a particular brand or name. Used to mark up a particular payment method and/or the financial product/service that supplies the card account.

Commonly used values:

  • http://purl.org/goodrelations/v1#AmericanExpress
  • http://purl.org/goodrelations/v1#DinersClub
  • http://purl.org/goodrelations/v1#Discover
  • http://purl.org/goodrelations/v1#JCB
  • http://purl.org/goodrelations/v1#MasterCard
  • http://purl.org/goodrelations/v1#VISA
http://schema.org/CreditCard.label: CreditCard

http://schema.org/CriticReview.comment: A CriticReview is a more specialized form of Review written or published by a source that is recognized for its reviewing activities. These can include online columns, travel and food guides, TV and radio shows, blogs and other independent Web sites. CriticReviews are typically more in-depth and professionally written. For simpler, casually written user/visitor/viewer/customer reviews, it is more appropriate to use the UserReview type. Review aggregator sites such as Metacritic already separate out the site's user reviews from selected critic reviews that originate from third-party sources.
http://schema.org/CriticReview.label: CriticReview

http://schema.org/CurrencyConversionServ.comment: A service to convert funds from one currency to another currency.
http://schema.org/CurrencyConversionServ.label: CurrencyConversionService

http://schema.org/DDxElement.comment: An alternative, closely-related condition typically considered later in the differential diagnosis process along with the signs that are used to distinguish it.
http://schema.org/DDxElement.label: DDxElement

http://schema.org/DanceGroup.comment: A dance group—for example, the Alvin Ailey Dance Theater or Riverdance.
http://schema.org/DanceGroup.label: DanceGroup

http://schema.org/DataFeed.comment: A single feed providing structured information about one or more entities or topics.
http://schema.org/DataFeed.label: DataFeed

http://schema.org/DataFeedItem.comment: A single item within a larger data feed.
http://schema.org/DataFeedItem.label: DataFeedItem

http://schema.org/DataType.comment: The basic data types such as Integers, Strings, etc.
http://schema.org/DataType.label: DataType

http://schema.org/Dataset.comment: A body of structured information describing some topic(s) of interest.
http://schema.org/Dataset.label: Dataset

http://schema.org/Date.comment: A date value in ISO 8601 date format.
http://schema.org/Date.label: Date

http://schema.org/DateTime.comment: A combination of date and time of day in the form [-]CCYY-MM-DDThh:mm:ss[Z|(+|-)hh:mm] (see Chapter 5.4 of ISO 8601).
http://schema.org/DateTime.label: DateTime

http://schema.org/DatedMoneySpecificatio.comment: A DatedMoneySpecification represents monetary values with optional start and end dates. For example, this could represent an employee's salary over a specific period of time. Note: This type has been superseded by MonetaryAmount use of that type is recommended
http://schema.org/DatedMoneySpecificatio.label: DatedMoneySpecification

http://schema.org/DayOfWeek.comment:
The day of the week, e.g. used to specify to which day the opening hours of an OpeningHoursSpecification refer.

Originally, URLs from GoodRelations were used (for Monday, Tuesday, Wednesday, Thursday, Friday, Saturday, Sunday plus a special entry for PublicHolidays); these have now been integrated directly into schema.org.
http://schema.org/DayOfWeek.label: DayOfWeek

http://schema.org/DeactivateAction.comment: The act of stopping or deactivating a device or application (e.g. stopping a timer or turning off a flashlight).
http://schema.org/DeactivateAction.label: DeactivateAction

http://schema.org/DefenceEstablishment.comment: A defence establishment, such as an army or navy base.
http://schema.org/DefenceEstablishment.label: DefenceEstablishment

http://schema.org/DeleteAction.comment: The act of editing a recipient by removing one of its objects.
http://schema.org/DeleteAction.label: DeleteAction

http://schema.org/DeliveryChargeSpecific.comment: The price for the delivery of an offer using a particular delivery method.
http://schema.org/DeliveryChargeSpecific.label: DeliveryChargeSpecification

http://schema.org/DeliveryEvent.comment: An event involving the delivery of an item.
http://schema.org/DeliveryEvent.label: DeliveryEvent

http://schema.org/DeliveryMethod.comment:
A delivery method is a standardized procedure for transferring the product or service to the destination of fulfillment chosen by the customer. Delivery methods are characterized by the means of transportation used, and by the organization or group that is the contracting party for the sending organization or person.

Commonly used values:

  • http://purl.org/goodrelations/v1#DeliveryModeDirectDownload
  • http://purl.org/goodrelations/v1#DeliveryModeFreight
  • http://purl.org/goodrelations/v1#DeliveryModeMail
  • http://purl.org/goodrelations/v1#DeliveryModeOwnFleet
  • http://purl.org/goodrelations/v1#DeliveryModePickUp
  • http://purl.org/goodrelations/v1#DHL
  • http://purl.org/goodrelations/v1#FederalExpress
  • http://purl.org/goodrelations/v1#UPS
http://schema.org/DeliveryMethod.label: DeliveryMethod
